[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{Who knows whether you should use a transfer or just bid 4\H yourself. Assume you decide on the transfer and bid 2\D. Partner bids 2\H (of course).  

Who knows whether you should use a transfer or just bid 4\H yourself. Assume you decide on the transfer and bid 2\D. Partner bids 2\H (of course). 

Naturally you go ahead and bid 4\H, the final contract.

The contract would be 4\H played by West.

East plays 4\H. South leads the \SQ and North follows with the \S9.

You win the first trick with the \SA.

Loser List: \S = 0 : \H = ? : \D = 2 : \C = 0 :: Total = ?

The loser count is very confused, but that \C suit is not confused at all. You want to be able to run the \Cs so your plan is to play the \H A K, and if both defenders follow go ahead and knock out the last \H so they can't ruff your \C tricks.

Unfortunately when you play \H A K, South plays the \HQ, then discards a \S. 

You may think you should change your plan but you should go right ahead with it. North has two master trumps, but dummy still has 4 small ones. So play a \H to force out North's \H10. He will no doubt play another \S and force dummy to ruff. No problem, knock out North's final \H and dummy will still have one tiny trump left. When you get back in you can run the \Cs unimpeded.

Usually it is good technique to leave master trump(s) undrawn.

The exception is when you have a long suit you wish to run and you can't stand to have the running stopped by a ruff.

This Deal is unusual in that there are two master trumps, but the principle is the same.}
[Play "W"]SQ

